@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@NEXT "Description"
@PREV "Main"
@{u}Introduction@{uu}

Collecting WWW addresses outside your WWW browser can be very laborious. You
either need to start your browser or load the hotlist into a text editor to
cut and paste them into the hotlist by hand.

This is why I wrote a script called GetHTTP, it would scan a message for WWW
addresses that start with "http://" and save them to the hotlist of your
browser. It was first written for Spot, but when I exchanged it for Thor I had
to rewrite it to use it for the new mail reader. Later on I wrote a similar
script that would scan for Email addresses (GetEmail) and add them to the Thor
userdatabase.

I then got the idea to join the two scripts together, because they both used
similar code. I changed the name of the script into GetNET and changed the GUI
to use listviews.

As of this version you will now also be able to scan for FTP addresses.
Another option is to create Aminet (FTP) download events when someone quotes
some files in the form of the Aminet INDEX. You can either scan one or more
selected messages in Thor or select a file on disk.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Description" "Description"
@NEXT "Requirements"
@PREV "Description"
@{u}Description@{uu}

GetNET is an ARexx script for Thor and has four options:
· grabbing of WWW addresses (GetHTTP)
· grabbing of FTP addresses (GetFTP)
· grabbing of Email addresses (GetEmail)
· grabbing of Aminet files (GetAminet)

Grabbing can be done from the current message, from a selected range of
messages or from a file on disk.

@{b}GetHTTP@{ub} will scan for WWW addreses.
The addresses can be saved to hotlists of:
· AMosaic
· AWeb
· IBrowse
· TCPdl
· Voyager
· HTML

@{b}GetFTP@{ub} will scan for FTP and IP addresses.
The addresses can be saved to hotlists of:
· AMosaic
· AWeb
· IBrowse
· Voyager
· HTML

and/or

· AmTFP
· DOpusFTP
· GUI-FTP
· ncFTPrecent

@{b}GetEmail@{ub} will scan for Email addresses.
The addresses can be saved to the userdatabase of your internet system.

@{b}GetAminet@{ub} will scan for Aminet files.
The files can be selected to create download events and download them using
Thor 2.4+.

All search schemes use special filtering routines designed to filter out as
much "junk" as possible.

GetNET.thor is copyright of Remco van Hooff.

Any bugs or problems, then please @{" contact " link "Author"} me.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "Requirements"
@PREV "Description"
@NEXT "Installation"
@{u}Requirements@{uu}

· Thor 2.4+

· ARexx installed and running

· COPY somewhere in your path

· A WWW browser for the WWW and/or FTP addresses
  Supported browsers are:
  · AMosaic
  · AWeb
  · IBrowse
  · TCPdl
  · Voyager
  HTML hotlists are also supported.

· Optional: AmFTP, DOpusFTP, GUI-FTP or ncFTP for FTP addresses
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
@NEXT "Configuration"
@PREV "Description"
@{u}Installation@{uu}

Use the provided installation script.

But for the ones who like to do it all by hand:
· copy GetNET.thor and CfgGetNET.thor to the rexx dir of Thor

After the installation start CfgGetNET.thor. Any existing config file is read
and automatiacly updated with a default setting when something is missing.

The default setting for a new or missing feature is always off.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Configuration" "Configuration"
@NEXT "Usage"
@PREV "Installation"
@{u}Configuration@{uu}

CfgGetNET.thor is the configuration editor of GetNET. It uses listviews to
control the editor.

The first listview shows 4 options
· Internet system
· Popup File/Msg requester
· File requester dir
· FTP save mode
and a link (Edit hotlists) to the listview where you can edit which hotlist to
use and where the hotlist can be found.

@{b}Internet system@{ub}
This is the system where you keep your Email userdatabase and also where the
Aminet download events will be created. This is usually your internet system.
Selecting this option will pop up a list of all your systems currently
configured in Thor.

@{b}Popup File/Msg requester@{ub}
When set to 'Yes' GetNET will always ask you if you want to scan the selected
message(s) or a file on disk. This option is an alternative to the @{" REQ " LINK "USAGE"}
switch which, if provided as an argument to GetNET, will scan a file on disk.

@{b}File requester dir@{ub}
This is the default directory the filerequester will open in when scanning a
file on disk.

@{b}FTP save mode@{ub}
Here you can select wether you want to save the FTP addresses to the WWW
hotlists:

· AMosaic
· AWeb
· IBrowse
· TCPdl
· Voyager
· HTML

and/or to the FTP hotlists:

· AmFTP
· DOpusFTP
· GUI-FTP
· ncFTPrecent

AmFTP needs to have a runing TCP/IP stack. You can enter a command in the AmFTP
configuration section to start a TCP/IP stack. This command will only be executed
if no TCP/IP stack is running.

@{b}FTP site name@{ub}
When set to Subject/filename the default ftp site description will be the
message subject, or the filename after scanning a file on disk. Setting it to
URL will GetNET  will use the ftp address as description.

@{b}Edit hotlists@{ub}
Selecting this link will bring up the WWW hotlists and, depending on your 'FTP save
mode' settings, the FTP hotlists. Selecting a hotlist will bring up a window
where you can select the path to the hotlist using a filerequester and an
option if you want to save to the hotlist.

You may save to multiple hotlists if desired.

Note: To save to the hotlist of AmFTP you need to select the AmFTP @{b}executable@{ub},
      not the hotlist. You will also need to have a TCP/IP stack running and
      preferable AmFTP also (both can be started by GetNET if configured
      correctly). GetNET will be aware if the TCP/IP stack and/or AmFTP isn't
      running and will ask if it should be started.

@{b}Filters@{ub}
GetNET's filters for filtering the addresses and files can be fine tuned. This
should only be done by @{" experienced " LINK "Filters"} users. I have covered
as much filters as possible so only in exceptional cases you need to edit them
and I therefore did not integrate it into CfgGetNET.

You might want to edit the filters when GetNET has trouble removing all the
garbage (unwanted characters that are not part of the actuall address).

If you are unsure about editing the filters, don't be affaid to @{" ask. " LINK "Author"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Filters" "Filters"
@{u}Filters@{uu}

GetNET has 3 kinds of filters:
· A filter for removing unwanted characters preceeding an address.
· A filter for removing unwanted characters trailing an address.
· A filter for filetype recognition by extension.

@{b}Addresses@{ub}
The first two kinds are known as filter.1.x for removing trailing characters
and filter.2.x for removing preceeding charactes, where x is the number of
filters starting at 1.

A filter character is a character that may be "connected" to an address,
e.g. <email@address.somewhere>
The '<' and '>' are not part of the actual address and thus should be
removed.
So filters for these characters are: filter.1.x = '>', filter.2.x = '<'
filter.1.x are used for chars that follow the address (http, email and ftp)
filter.2.x are used for chars that preceed the address (email and ftp)

The '.' is "hardcoded" and is therefore not included in the filter list.

Also included are 3 control characters (cr: carriage return, lf: linefeed and
tab: tabulator). You may add more of these characters. Be sure they are
defined a hexadecimals. When adding them to the filter list(s) do @{b}not@{ub} put any
quotes (double or single) around then.

@{b}Filetypes@{ub}
These filters are used to recognize files in FTP URLs, based on their
extension. These are not mandatory. They will only add something to the
cosmetic value of GetNET. So if you want to see as many files in your FTP
description you just need to add the extension in UPPER case and enclosed in
quotes.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Usage"
@NEXT "Legal stuff"
@PREV "Installation"
@{u}Usage@{uu}

@{b}Arguments@{ub}
GetNET can have one argument:

REQ/S

If given this switch will pop up a filerequester asking for a file on disk.
This file will then be scanned by the option selected from the requester
following the filerequester. 
This switch is an alternative to the 'Popup File/Msg requester' option in the
configuration. Setting 'Popup File/Msg requester' to 'Yes' will always pop up a
requester asking if you want to scan a message(s) or a file.

@{b}Options@{ub}
The main requester offers 5 options:
· @{" HTTP   " LINK "HTTP"}
· @{" Email  " LINK "Email"}
· @{" FTP    " LINK "FTP"}
· @{" Aminet " LINK "Aminet"}
· Quit

Selecting 'quit' will exit GetNET.

@ENDNODE

