@NODE "HTTP" "HTTP"
@NEXT "Email"
@PREV "Usage"

@{u}HTTP@{uu}

This options will scan for WWW addresses and lets you save them to your
hotlist(s).

While scanning a progress window will open also showing the number of
addresses as they are found.

The addresses found will be shown in a listview where you can (multi)select
the ones you want to save to your hotlist. If no addresses are found you will
be notified by a requester and GetNET will exit.

Next another listview will show the selected addresses.
You can now select an address to give it a name. Only the first 20 characters
of the name will be shown in the listview, but the full name is saved to the
hotlist. If you leave the name empty GetNET will use the subject of the massage
or the filename if it's a file on disk as a default. The default names will be
numbered to make them unique.
Selecting 'SAVE' will save the addresses exit GetNET.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Email" "Email"
@NEXT "FTP"
@PREV "HTTP"

@{u}Email@{uu}

This options will scan for Email addresses and lets you save them to your
userdatabase of your internet system.

While scanning a progress window will open also showing the number of
addresses as they are found.

The addresses found will be shown in a listview where you can (multi)select
the ones you want to save to your hotlist. If no addresses are found you will
be notified by a requester and GetNET will exit.

Next another listview will show the selected addresses.
You can now select an address to edit the userdata. Another listview will open
where you can edit the name, the address, an alias and a comment.
Selecting the name will pop up a requester asking for you to enter the name of
the person/server the email address belongs to. You can either enter it by
hand or select 'From:' which will get the name of the sender of the message.
Leaving the name option empty will result that a default name will be used
which is the part infront of the '@' in the email address. Alias and comment
will remain empty if nothing is entered.
'RETURN' will return to the previous listview where you can select 'SAVE' to
save the addresses and exit GetNET.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FTP" "FTP"
@NEXT "Aminet"
@PREV "Email"

@{u}FTP@{uu}

This options will scan for FTP addresses and lets you save them to your
hotlist(s).

It works the same way @{" HTTP " LINK "HTTP"} does.

Except for the FTP description when saving to AmFTP, DOpusFTP or GUI-FTP. If
GetNET encounters a file in the FTP URL it will add the filename to the FTP
description enclosed in brackets.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Aminet" "Aminet"
@NEXT "Usage"
@PREV "FTP"

@{u}Aminet@{uu}

This options will scan for Aminet files and create download events for them
in your internet system.

It can find files from the output produced by InsertIt.thor (© by Shaun
Downend) or in a format similar to that of the RECENT or INDEX files on
Aminet.

While scanning a progress window will open, showing the number of files as
they are found.

The files found will be shown in a listview where you can (multi)select
the ones you want to download. If no files are found you will
be notified by a requester and GetNET will exit.

Note:
If you haven't upgraded Thor to version 2.4, you can download the files by using
ncFTPevents.br (© by Shaun Downend). Be sure to configure your system to accept
downloads. See the ncFTPevents distribution or Thor documents on how to do that.
@ENDNODE

